Dear Friends,



=B7         Global markets are entering the final quarter of 2021 with a mo=
unting number of headwinds.

=B7         Most developed economies rebounded from the pandemic. Focus of =
central banks led by the US Federal Reserve is now switching to timing of a=
 reduction in monetary stimulus. Five Central Banks have already raised int=
erest rates.

=B7         The post-pandemic reopening has unleashed pent-up demand and in=
creased inflationary pressures. We expect these pressures to decelerate as =
the global economy gradually normalises, but this process may be delayed by=
 rising energy prices.

=B7         A reduction in monetary stimulus should be positive for the US =
dollar. We expect it to continue to appreciate versus other currencies.

=B7         Weaker Central bank support and a normalisation of the economy =
should lead to higher long-term bond yields and more volatile financial mar=
kets in the coming months.

=B7         In the context of higher volatility and inflationary pressure, =
diversification remains key. Gold, inflation-linked bonds and alternatives =
provide such diversification

Shabbat Shalom, have a nice weekend.

Moshe


Moshe Langerman
